message:
I'm using a third party library to convert a PDF to a Tiff. This library doesn't provide async methods. I've written a method that calls this library to convert a PDF in my MCV API web (HTTP) service. I then called this method using Task.Run which I now realize isn't correct. Is there any way to make this I/O bound method async?  

My code looks like:  
var success = await Task.Run(() => ConvertToTiff(filename));

Sure, you can just do this:

 var _ = CacheMyDataToDisk(myData);

Note that this assumes that the method being called does not introduce any functional differences if it is not called, handles all its own exceptions, and does not attempt to resume on its context (e.g., the ASP.NET context may be disposed before this method completes).

Hey Stephen.

I have an example of an IO bound call where I'm not sure how to avoid Task.Run():

async Task<byte[]> GetMyData()   
{  
 var myData = await DownloadMyData():  
 await CacheMyDataToDisk(myData);  
 return myData;  
}

Since it is not necessary for the function to await the caching, how would you avoid using Task.Run()? Calling CacheMyDataToDisk without await throws a warning and introduces issues with exception handling. Is that really the way to go?

Thanks for the articles!  
Anders

I just ran a test and am definitely not getting any warnings with this code:

 private static async Task<byte[]> GetMyData()  
 {  
 await Task.Delay(1000);  
 var _ = Task.Delay(1000);  
 return null;  
}

If Chris L's situation were like the following, would that then become a valid use of Task.Run?

var t1 = Task.Run(() => ConvertToTiff(filename1));  
var t2 = Task.Run(() => ConvertToTiff(filename2));  
var file1 = await t1;  
var file2 = await t2;  
return Merge(file1, file2);

